aming it for the Asian city his father had visited, Raphael Welles built Samarkand, a two-thousand-acre showplace in the North Carolina sandhills. He set out twenty-four thousand peach trees and bred horses before failed crops forced him to sell.","number":2},{"category":"religion","header":"A Bahá'í who spoke for the faith","body":"From 1938 Raphael Welles lectured on the Bahá'í Faith across New York and as far as Idaho, and in 1948 served as a Bahá'í delegate to a United Nations religious conference. His parents had hosted 'Abdu'l-Bahá in 1912.","number":3}],"sources":[],"institutions":[],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"research_tags":[],"cross_connections":[{"type":"in_law","related_id":"X03114","display_label":"was his father-in-law; Union general who led troops into Richmond"}],"quotes":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"statues":[],"bio":{"first_name":"Raphael Welles","last_name":"Pumpelly","married_names":[],"display_name":"Raphael Welles Pumpelly","gender":"male","photo_url":"https://res.cloudinary.com/dc5clrqtw/image/upload/v1780758541/18514327_1449951758_fascop.jpg"},"military_service":[],"slug":"raphael-welles-pumpelly-1881"},"I01543":{"id":"I01543","former_ids":[],"is_placeholder":false,"has_descendants_documented":false,"gender":"female","birth":{"year":1883,"month":6,"day":3,"city":"New York","state":"New York","country":"United States"},"death":{"year":1963,"month":9,"day":27,"city":"Los Angeles","state":"California","country":"United States"},"classification":{"is_thomas_descendant":false,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_thomas_spouse":false,"is_talcott_spouse":true,"include_in_path_calculation":false,"descent_paths_to_thomas":0,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":false,"descent_from_john_talcott":false,"is_progenitor":false,"is_easter_egg":false},"notable":{"is_notable":false,"notable_category":[]},"parents":{"father_id":"X03114","father_name":"Brig. Gen. Edward Hastings Ripley","mother_id":"X03115","mother_name":"Amelia Dyckman Van Doren Ripley"},"number_of_marriages":1,"marriages":[{"spouse_id":"TD0337","spouse_name":"Raphael Welles Pumpelly","children_ids":["TD0345","TD0346","TD0347"],"notes":"Divorced 1942."}],"tags":[],"narrative_blocks":[{"category":"family","header":"A general's granddaughter who married a Pumpelly","body":"Amelie Sybil Van Doren Ripley was a daughter of the Civil War general Edward Hastings Ripley. She married Raphael Welles Pumpelly in a celebrated 1909 double wedding at New York's Grace Church.","number":1},{"category":"character","header":"Her lavish living drained the family fortune","body":"Amelie's spending, including gifts to the Christian Science church, helped push the Pumpellys toward ruin by 1918. Her 1925 separation from Raphael Welles, on grounds of infidelity, drew newspaper coverage across several states.","number":2}],"sources":[],"institutions":[],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"research_tags":[],"cross_connections":[],"quotes":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"statues":[],"bio":{"first_name":"Amelie Sybil","last_name":"Ripley","married_names":[],"display_name":"Amelie Sybil Van Doren Ripley","gender":"female"},"military_service":[],"slug":"amelie-sybil-ripley-1883"},"TD0345":{"id":"TD0345","former_ids":[],"is_placeholder":false,"has_descendants_documented":false,"gender":"female","birth":{"year":1910,"month":5,"day":10,"city":"New York","state":"New York","country":"United States"},"death":{"year":1951,"month":11,"day":3,"city":"Mexico City","country":"Mexico"},"classification":{"is_thomas_descendant":false,"is_talcott_descendant":true,"is_thomas_spouse":false,"is_talcott_spouse":false,"include_in_path_calculation":true,"descent_paths_to_thomas":0,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":false,"descent_from_john_talcott":true,"is_progenitor":false,"is_easter_egg":false,"generation_from_john_talcott":8},"notable":{"is_notable":false,"notable_category":[]},"parents":{"father_id":"TD0337","father_name":"Raphael Welles Pumpelly","mother_id":"I01543","mother_name":"Amelie Sybil Van Doren Ripley"},"number_of_marriages":1,"marriages":[{"spouse_id":"I01549","spouse_name":"John Henry Bates","children_ids":["TD0354","TD0355","TD0356","TD0357"],"marriage_year":1935,"marriage_place":"Manhattan, New York"}],"tags":[],"narrative_blocks":[{"category":"family","header":"She crossed the color line in 1935","body":"A New York socialite by birth, Amelie married the African-American boxer and cabinetmaker John Henry Bates in 1935, when such unions were illegal in many states. As Bahá'ís, the couple held to the faith's teaching of the oneness of humankind.","number":1},{"category":"character","header":"From socialite to labor-union poster artist","body":"Born to wealth, Amelie became a painter who made graphic designs and posters for a labor union. She and John moved among the Black artists and writers of the late Harlem Renaissance.","number":2},{"category":"character","header":"Her Vermont farm sparked 'Invisible Man'","body":"The family kept an ancestral farm at Fayston, Vermont, where their friend Ralph Ellison stayed during the war. Ellison later credited the visits as a direct spark for his novel Invisible Man.","number":3},{"category":"death","header":"She died on a Bahá'í mission abroad","body":"After teaching the Bahá'í Faith in Haiti, Amelie moved with her family toward Mexico City. She died there suddenly of a coronary embolism in 1951, at the age of forty-one.","number":4}],"sources":[],"institutions":[],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"research_tags":[],"cross_connections":[],"quotes":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"statues":[],"bio":{"first_name":"Amelie Welles","last_name":"Bates","married_names":[],"display_name":"Amelie Welles Pumpelly Bates","gender":"female","photo_url":"https://res.cloudinary.com/dc5clrqtw/image/upload/v1780758616/178937192_1602251134_fk9xzz.jpg"},"military_service":[],"slug":"amelie-welles-bates-1910"},"TD0346":{"id":"TD0346","former_ids":[],"is_placeholder":false,"has_descendants_documented":false,"gender":"male",